Flower Child continues to be the darling brand of The Cheesecake Factory Inc., which reported fourth-quarter earnings after market on Wednesday.&nbsp;

The 44-unit fast-casual chain continues to resonate well with guests, president David Gordon told investors.

“We are enthusiastic and very pleased with the performance of Flower Child,” he said. “It continues to exceed expectations in new and existing markets, which I think is very promising.”

He said the concept, which is health-oriented with a scratch kitchen and many vegan and gluten-free options, continues to expand, including an opening last month.&nbsp;

“As we move into new markets, even when there has been no Flower Child within miles, or states, the reception has been very, very strong. So it's resonating with consumers, I think for a few reasons: It's very healthy, on trend, and delicious, and it's an experiential fast-casual dining experience. It's not transactional. And today we continually say that we believe all of our guests are looking for experiences versus transactions.”

He said the operations team at the chain has also put systems in place over the past 24 months that “enable consistent execution.”

“When we look at the type of reviews we're getting in social media, or even just through our own channels, (they) are very, very positive, and that's because of the consistent execution. So we feel good that the concept is certainly in a place where it can accelerate. The only thing that's holding us back from growing a little bit faster than maybe a 20% (annual) growth rate would be that we want to make sure we have the right people-power in place. We need the right leadership at the general manager and executive chef level to open up those very visual, very busy, fast-casual units.”

The company said in its Wednesday filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission that Flower Child has the potential to grow to 700 domestic locations “over time.”

Flower Child’s same-store sales for the quarter were up 4%, giving it a two-year comparable sales increase of 15%. Its annualized average unit volume was $4.3 million for the quarter and $4.6 million for the year. Restaurant-level margins for mature locations was 17.5% for the quarter and $19.5% for the year.

Although the company’s flagship brand, 216-unit Cheesecake Factory, saw a 2.2% dip in same-store sales over the fourth quarter, ended Dec. 30, 2025, and its second-largest brand, 48-unit North Italia, saw comps decrease by 4%, Gordon as well as chief executive officer board chair David Overton and chief financial officer Matt Clark said they were pleased with the company’s performance, with a record number of openings in 2025 and improved guest-satisfaction metrics.&nbsp;

Story Continues

The company opened 25 restaurants over the course of the year — around 7% unit growth in total — including seven restaurants in the fourth quarter: two Cheesecake Factory restaurants, two North Italia locations, one Flower Child, and three Fox Restaurant Concepts restaurants.

The company also had record total revenues of $961.6 million, up from $921 million in the fourth quarter of 2024, and record EBITDA of $354 million. Net income was $28.8 million, or 60 cents per share.

Restaurant-level profit margins at The Cheesecake Factory increased 60 basis points year-over-year to 17.6%, Overton said, adding that margins also improved at North Italia and Flower Child.

The company also operates 55 Fox Restaurant Concepts under multiple brands as well as six Grand Lux Café restaurants, having closed its Houston location last month. It also closed two Cheesecake Factory restaurants and one Bianco location in January, and opened one Flower Child. Gordon said no other restaurant closures were planned for the year.&nbsp;

Looking ahead, Clark said he expected revenue in the first quarter of 2026 of $955 million to $977 million and around $3.9 billion for the year. He said company expects to open “as many as” 26 restaurants this year, with around three quarters of them in the second half of the year. That would include six Cheesecake Factories, six to seven each of North Italia and Flower Child, and seven Fox Restaurant Concepts.&nbsp;

Gordon reiterated plans to launch an app for Cheesecake Factory in the second quarter of 2026, following the introduction of an awards program in mid-2023.&nbsp;

“Our goal is to continue to make members’ experience as seamless as possible and give them as much value as they can as members,” he said of the app. “We're going to be very focused on the app making the guest experience easier — so easier access to reservations … being able to see things like their order history (and) repeat their order history, and we're excited to get it going into Q2.”

Cheesecake Factory Inc. Q4 by the numbers

The Cheesecake Factory: $681.4 million revenue, up1.8% from a year ago

North Italia: $88.2 million revenue, up 8.5%

Fox Restaurant Concepts: $99.4 million revenue, up 16%

&nbsp;

Cheesecake Factory Inc. fiscal 2025 by the numbers

The Cheesecake Factory: $2.7 billion revenue, up 1%

North Italia: $345.9 million, up 15.5%

Fox Restaurant Concepts: $355 million, up 18.3%

